{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480285"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:40:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:40:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"34"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/34"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.24,0.24,0.02,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"34"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109938"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/34"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"34"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92296"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10055"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14051"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44608"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109938"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner for a routine health check. As part of this, and with informed consent regarding the risks and benefits of testing, the GP requests a Prostate Specific Antigen (PSA).  His PSA returns as 10.8 \u00b5g/mL (Reference range for his age: 0.3-6.6 \u00b5g/L). A prostate biopsy confirms he has Gleason 4+4=8 prostate adenocarcinoma. He does not have any lower urinary tract symptoms. His medical history includes hypertension and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease. Two months ago he had a ST elevation myocardial infarction and was treated with drug-eluding stent insertion. He currently takes aspirin and clopidogrel for this.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Watchful waiting","Radical prostatectomy","Radiotherapy","Chemotherapy","Androgen deprivation therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe varieties of treatment for prostate cancer are complicated and contentious at the best of times. As an area of practice, it is constantly changing. Currently prostate cancer management is guided by an assessment of the patient\u0027s risk category as well as each individual\u0027s co-morbidity burden and life-expectancy. This man has D\u0027Amico High Risk prostate cancer based on the Gleason score of 4+4 = 8 and PSA \u0026gt;10 \u00b5g/mL. Should his life-expectancy be greater than 10 years then he should be offered some form of active intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate in this patient. This management strategy is suitable for patients with a life-expectancy of \u0026lt;10 years. In this option, a patient\u0027s PSA is monitored and they are assessed for the presence of metastatic disease. Should the disease metastasis or should they have symptoms related to locally advanced prostate cancer then ADT is instituted to keep the disease under control with the understanding that the patient will likely die with their prostate cancer and not from their prostate cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgery\u003C/strong\u003E to remove the entire prostate and seminal vesicles is inappropriate for this patient because of the recent myocardial infarction and current need to remain on dual anti-platelet therapy. This option is especially incorrect because non-invasive treatment options exist for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct treatment option based on this patient\u0027s risk category and co-morbidities precluding more invasive procedures. For early prostate cancer, the mortality outcomes for surgery and radiotherapy are equal and men should be offered each modality of treatment. Radiotherapy is delivered either in the form of external beam radiotherapy (EBRT) or brachytherapy. This patient is unsuitable for brachytherapy as it is invasive, requires a general anaesthetic and he would need to hold his clopidogrel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients with visceral metastases or high metastatic burden and is given in the palliative setting. This man is potentially curable and so chemotherapy is inappropriate at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAndrogen deprivation therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (ADT) is provided to patients with metastatic prostate cancer or as adjuvant therapy to patients before and after radiotherapy. If the patient elects to have treatment with radiotherapy he may receive ADT as part of this treatment but it should not be used as the sole treatment modality in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with prostate cancer with a life expectancy less than 10 years, watchful waiting may be an appropriate management approach"],"references":["Mottet N, Bellmunt J, Bolla M, Briers E, Cumberbatch MG, De Santis M, et al. EAU-ESTRO-SIOG Guidelines on Prostate Cancer. Part 1: Screening, Diagnosis, and Local Treatment with Curative Intent. Eur Urol. 2017;71(4):618-29.","Pullar B, Shah N. Prostate cancer. Surgery. 2016;34(10):505-511"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92296"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"34"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92296"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T17:12:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T17:12:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"34"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109938"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"112","links":